   winning advertiser tends to have a lower profit margin under the CPA
   model than under the CPC model. We identify the conditions under which
   the CPA model leads to higher publisher (or advertiser) payoffs than the
   CPC model. Whether publishers (or advertisers) prefer the CPA model over
   the CPC model depends on the advertisers' risk aversion, uncertainty in
   the product market, and the presence of advertisers with low immediate
   sales ratios. Our findings indicate a conflict of interest between
   publishers and advertisers in their preferences for these two pricing
   models. We further consider which pricing model offers greater social
   welfare.
